^-|CP||AT|^c@2^Y@3^*B"Constructive Raise" and "Single Raise" are just a terminology issue, and the terminology is not universally understood.

The simplest terminology is to think of 1@H-P-2@H as a "Single Raise." I play it shows 6-9 (occasionally 5) with exactly 3-card support. That means if you bid a forcing 1NT over 1 of a major, you cannot have 3-card support.

Another way to play, which I do not like, is that a single raise is a bit stronger, say 8-10 or even 8-11. If you play that, then the single raise is called a "Constructive Raise." With 3-card support and 6-7 you first bid a forcing NT and then correct to 2 of opener's major.

I don't like playing that a single raise is "constructive" (e.g. 8-11), because a) opener cannot tell whether or not you have 3-card support and b) if you raise immediately it takes up more bidding room and makes it more difficult for the opponents. As usual "support with support" whenever you can.

Howard Schutzman^*n|
