^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You could make a case for either pass or 4@S. In IMPs I prefer 4@S. in Match Points I prefer 3N. But lots of times it won't make any difference. If you always raise with 3, I think you will be right more often than not, especially at IMPs. On this hand, absent a diamond lead you make 4 spades 3 hearts 2 clubs and a diamond for 10 tricks, so you make the same ## of NT as spades.|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And actually if they shift to a diamond after winning the spade, Kia  has to worry. Some people feel with 4-3-3-3 distribution and not 4-card support you should always play 3N. But my feeling is that 4@S is usually safer. Therefore, in IMPs you should bid 4 of the major. Occasionally partner will have a hand that wants to play in slam if there is a fit, but in 3N if there is not. So in IMPs I always bid 4@S if I have 3-card support. But in Match Points, it is more complicated because often you make the same ## of tricks in NT and spades and making 4N in match points is a better score than making 4@S.|
